description:
PlayerContext.tsx::updateMiniRect (L243-265) calls saveMiniRect(next) and playerEnterMinimize(...) INSIDE the setMiniRect updater closure:

  const updateMiniRect = useCallback((updates) => {
    setMiniRect((prev) => {
      const next = { ...prev, ...updates };
      if (/* identity short-circuit */) return prev;
      saveMiniRect(next);              // ← side effect inside reducer
      if (isMinimizedRef.current) {
        playerEnterMinimize(...);      // ← IPC inside reducer
      }
      return next;
    });
  }, []);

React explicitly requires state-updater callbacks to be pure: StrictMode double-invokes them in dev, which means the IPC fires twice in dev. The identity short-circuit mitigates duplicate localStorage writes but the contract is wrong.

Proposed:
- Strip the side effects from the updater. Just return next (or prev if identity-equal).
- Add useEffect(() => { saveMiniRect(miniRect); if (isMinimized) playerEnterMinimize(...) }, [miniRect, isMinimized]) at the provider level.
- The identity-short-circuit becomes unnecessary because effects only run on actual dep change.

Acceptance:
- updateMiniRect updater is pure (returns prev or next, no IPC/localStorage calls)
- Dev-mode (StrictMode) no longer fires double IPC on a single drag commit
- PlayerContext.test.tsx still passes (may need adjustment if it asserted the side-effect order)
- Manual: drag mini to a different corner, verify the persisted localStorage matches and the mpv host re-snaps

Small task; ~30 LOC moved.

## Required Skills
react, prexu, anti-fabrication
